	<td class="alt2" width="175">
	
	
			<div id="postmenu_1228762">
				
				
				<a class="bigusername" href="member.php?u=13001">jhorry</a>
				<script type="text/javascript"> vbmenu_register("postmenu_1228762", true); </script>
				
			</div>
			
			<div class="smallfont">Forum Wizard</div>
			
			
			
		




			<div class="smallfont">

<!-- Profiles -->
 
<!-- / Profiles -->



				&nbsp;<br />
				<div>   </div>
			</div>				
	
	
	
	</td>
	
	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_1228762">
	
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_1228762">
                  
                  As I have said in the past, i think we should look at the real purpose of stances:<br />
<br />
They are NOT ment to gain a temporary boost to some skills while a temporary decrease to others, while being able to quickly shift back to a previous state.<br />
<br />
They are NOT ment to be macroed to all your skills. We should be shifting the gears, not driving an automatic.<br />
<br />
They ARE ment to add a bit of flexability to a class so that they can adjust while fighting in combat.<br />
<br />
<br />
(skip to the bottom if you want to see what i boil our Barriers down to in order for our class to be able to switch and adapt to different senerios w/o worrying about stance dancing)<br />
<br />
Why have stances? <br />
<br />
So when we are happily blasting out our dps and then suddenly take a large aoe spell to the face and almost die, we can go &quot;oh, might be wise to switch to a more spell defensive mode,&quot; and use Chromatic accordingly.<br />
<br />
<br />
Really, i would support the change from abilities to stances, provided the following:<br />
<br />
1.) 10 second wait time when switching into a stance before you can switch out of it. <br />
<br />
2.) An increased energy cost for switching to a new stance.<br />
<br />
This prevents stance dancing altogether and supports a tactical decision making before switching stances.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
I also think our Barriers need some serious revision so that they can be competitve choices in all aspects of game play (aka, solo, group, and raiding we might have use for the all)<br />
<br />
<br />
<b>Flame Barrier</b>: Why does this make us more efficient? Our fire spells are conceptualized to be our &quot;high damage, less efficient&quot; spells, so this just doesnt make sense.<br />
<br />
A better option would likely be for this to increase our damage and our energy cost of our nukes, allowing us to reach a higher short term dps at the cost of a weaker long term dps. <br />
<br />
As a sorcerer, this is obviously a key concept of the class., and would have many uses.<br />
<br />
Would see a lot of use in fast paced situations, so great for grouping or soloing, and for maximum dps potiential in certain raiding situations.<br />
<br />
Pick what ever numbers you feel are appropriate.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<b>Force Barrier:</b> Now this one is definatly up for debate, but i personally would not in any way shape or form, use this while raiding, when compared to the current Flame Barrier. How then to make this useful?<br />
<br />
Let us look at our spells. Arcane spells give feedback, and generally are more efficient than any of our other nukes, shouldnt the barrier then reflect this?<br />
<br />
What i would do is simply move the current effects of Flame Barrier to the Force Barrier, and add in an AoE &quot;Damage&quot; Immunity.<br />
<br />
<br />
What does this accomplish?<br />
<br />
This would be a safe and efficient stance, one that we use when we are unsure about what the encounter is going to throw at us.<br />
<br />
The AoE damage immunity is not overpowering, it is used in several games and almost always has something to counter balance it.<br />
<br />
In this case, we are doing less quick damage compared to Flame Barrier, but share a higher survivability as well as more efficient damage.<br />
<br />
<br />
This combination makes sence, on a long fight, you definatly want to live through it to maximize your dps, and you want to be able to deliver your dps over a long span of time, so *should* come into play if balanced correctly.<br />
<br />
Good for grouping and soloing as well if you never want to slow down.<br />
<br />
<b>Chromatic Barrier:</b><br />
This one should, imo, be expanded to incorperate similar abilities.<br />
<br />
I think this stance should capitalize on our anti-spell abilities to agreat degree, focusing in on our sub-role.<br />
<br />
How could we do this? Im open to suggestions, but what I have considered:<br />
<br />
1.) Increase the chance to land our counter spells.<br />
<br />
(if we get Emilia's chances to our wards)<br />
<br />
2.) Increase the amount of protection from our wards.<br />
<br />
3.) Keep the resistance and auto-reflect / disperse on us personally.<br />
<br />
<br />
I could see this being really useful against caster raid mobs, we would have excellent protection capability, would personally be very hard to kill (3 shots at most in a time frame to even come close to killing us), and our counter spells would be much more potient than any other caster's.<br />
<br />
Certainly would be useful outside of raiding as well, as soloing caster mobs and grouping against casters, we would offer very good protection.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
I would also like to propose a 4th barrier, to cover the only aspect of our class that we have not touched base on:<br />
<br />
<b>Frost Barrier</b><br />
<br />
What part of our class is left for us to tap into? Why, our self preservation.<br />
<br />
I propose that this be our barrier of choice if we know we are in a situation where we will likely steal hate and be attacked.<br />
<br />
<br />
There are several ways we could make this a viable choice for both solo, grouping, and raiding:<br />
<br />
First of all, this Barrier would have a regenerating triggered effect (just like Chromatic) that triggers when a foe lands a melee attack:<br />
<br />
1.) This would completely absorb the attack, preventing 100% damage from one attack.<br />
<br />
2.) This would root the foe for 2 seconds, and then snare them for 50% for 5 seconds (would root a raid mob only, no snare effect)<br />
<br />
This would have a 15 second recharge effect.<br />
<br />
Secondly, this Barrier would have a hate modification, lowering our hate gain by 25%.<br />
<br />
<br />
Now, how in a raiding situation would this possibly useful without being over powered? Simple:<br />
<br />
Memory wiping foes.<br />
<br />
Now, what class would you assume would do the most spike damage potientially right after a memwipe, there fore likely being the target of choice?<br />
<br />
Yea, us probably. So, with this Barrier on, not only are we generating less hate once the Memwipe happens, we also have a 1 shot Rune to absorb one swing from the raid mob, and it will be rooted in place for 2 seconds, allowing us to back away and giving the tank enough time to get things undercontrol.<br />
<br />
If we were in any other stance, we would likely die in this situation if we gained hate.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
So, to sum things up:<br />
<br />
<br />
Flame Barrier:<br />
<br />
Great for fast paced action, if we see that we really need to risk it all to kill somthing 'Right Fucking Now,&quot; then we would switch to this.<br />
<br />
Optimal encounter- &quot;Burn&quot; encounters<br />
<br />
Force Barrier:<br />
<br />
Great for an all-around stance, good if we dont know how the fight will progress and great for long, drawn out fights or fights where we might be AoE squished.<br />
<br />
Optimal encounter- &quot;Endurance&quot; encounters<br />
<br />
Chromatic Barrier:<br />
<br />
Amazing against spell casting foes, and would be one of the main reasons to bring a sorcerer along side our great dps potiential.<br />
<br />
Optimal encounter- Caster encounters<br />
<br />
Frost Barrier:<br />
<br />
A awsome barrier when we know a foe is likely to jump us, this is our &quot;careful&quot; barrier for when we stand a high chance of being the center of attention.<br />
<br />
Optimal encounter- Memwipe encounters
                  
		</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td class="alt2">
